115
00:06:44.356 --> 00:06:48.036
So what is a senescent cell? Well, the history of the field

116
00:06:48.156 --> 00:06:51.196
has really looked at senescence in

117
00:06:51.296 --> 00:06:53.996
vitro. So first looking at the Hayflick

118
00:06:54.816 --> 00:06:56.536
limit and replicative senescence.

119
00:06:57.376 --> 00:07:01.016
So after cells have been cultured for a long time, they stop

120
00:07:01.056 --> 00:07:03.396
proliferating, as is connected with

121
00:07:03.996 --> 00:07:06.296
decrease in telomeres.

122
00:07:07.136 --> 00:07:10.916
It was also recognized there was stress-induced senescence that could

123
00:07:10.956 --> 00:07:14.556
be stimulated by oxidative stress, genotoxic, and

124
00:07:14.616 --> 00:07:18.336
oncogenic stress, and the proliferative stress being

125
00:07:18.376 --> 00:07:22.356
another mechanism. But much of this has been studied

126
00:07:22.396 --> 00:07:23.016
in vitro.

127
00:07:24.216 --> 00:07:27.936
So these cells were characterized with a number of markers.

128
00:07:28.396 --> 00:07:28.656
So

129
00:07:29.696 --> 00:07:31.216
beta-gal, for example,

130
00:07:32.656 --> 00:07:36.056
HMGB1, movement from the nucleus to the

131
00:07:36.096 --> 00:07:39.176
