619
00:36:00.770 --> 00:36:04.440
So as Jennifer had alluded to, senescence goes beyond just aging, what Hayflick and

620
00:36:04.450 --> 00:36:06.590
Moorhead first defined it as. It's really a

621
00:36:06.670 --> 00:36:10.290
conserved physiological stress response to damage.

622
00:36:10.910 --> 00:36:14.550
There are a number of stimuli that can induce it, telomere shortening, DNA

623
00:36:14.630 --> 00:36:18.350
damage, reactive oxygen species, common oncogenes such as

624
00:36:18.430 --> 00:36:22.400
RAS, and common conventional cancer therapies like chemo and

625
00:36:22.430 --> 00:36:26.330
radiotherapy. The first really solid intrinsic hallmark that

626
00:36:26.410 --> 00:36:30.110
I think most of us are aware of is this stable cell cycle arrest that's

627
00:36:30.150 --> 00:36:34.030
mediated by these two tumor suppressor pathways, p53 driving p21

628
00:36:34.730 --> 00:36:38.350
and p16 by inhibiting CDK4/6 kinase activity,

629
00:36:38.510 --> 00:36:41.990
activating Rb to both transcriptionally and epigenetically

630
00:36:42.070 --> 00:36:46.006
repress cell cycle genes.In addition to these cells being arrested, they're

631
00:36:46.106 --> 00:36:49.846
also persistent because they're resistant to cell

632
00:36:49.866 --> 00:36:53.526
death, such as apoptosis, by upregulating anti-apoptotic

633
00:36:53.586 --> 00:36:56.346
pathways such as BCL2 family members.

634
00:36:57.166 --> 00:37:00.596
Given these cells don't proliferate and they upregulate tumor suppressors, it was

635
00:37:00.626 --> 00:37:04.226
first surmised that this is a tumor-suppressive process.

636
00:37:04.346 --> 00:37:07.986
Indeed, there are a number of landmark studies in 2005, including from Dr.

637
00:37:08.226 --> 00:37:12.136
Smith's lab. They really were able to identify markers of oncogene-induced

638
00:37:12.146 --> 00:37:15.286
senescence in non-proliferative premalignant lesions.

639
00:37:15.366 --> 00:37:19.326
So what do we mean by that? So here's an example, KRAS-driven lung cancer from

640
00:37:19.366 --> 00:37:22.826
Manu Serrano's group. So on the right here, we have an adenoma.

641
00:37:22.866 --> 00:37:25.466
This is a premalignant lesion, hasn't become invasive yet.

642
00:37:25.526 --> 00:37:29.306
On the left here, we have an adenocarcinoma, which is considered malignant.

643
00:37:29.386 --> 00:37:32.986
Using this canonical marker of senescence, senescence-associated beta-gal,

644
00:37:34.006 --> 00:37:37.926
we can see the premalignant lesion stains beautifully for SA-beta-gal, but

645
00:37:37.986 --> 00:37:40.986
as the tumor progresses, it loses this senescence marker.

646
00:37:42.206 --> 00:37:46.126
And there's been really nice mouse models here from the Pandolfi lab in a different

647
00:37:46.186 --> 00:37:49.716
model here in prostate cancer losing PTEN to activate the

648
00:37:49.786 --> 00:37:53.206
PI3K pathway in these premalignant intraepithelial

649
00:37:53.246 --> 00:37:56.626
neoplasias, again, staining beautifully for beta-gal, and then

650
00:37:57.126 --> 00:38:01.116
having the need for additional tumor suppressor loss to bypass senescence,

651
00:38:01.166 --> 00:38:04.806
suggesting this might be a barrier to full malignancy.

652
00:38:05.766 --> 00:38:09.746
However, as we went into the 2010s and beyond, the development of a number of

653
00:38:09.786 --> 00:38:13.416
mouse models using two of our most canonical markers of senescence,

654
00:38:13.546 --> 00:38:17.416
p16 and p21, to track these to temporarily and

655
00:38:17.466 --> 00:38:21.106
spatially deplete them, and development of drugs called senolytic

656
00:38:21.206 --> 00:38:24.886
drugs to target these anti-apoptotic pathways or

657
00:38:24.906 --> 00:38:28.326
P53 pathways that allow senescent cells to persist,

658
00:38:28.826 --> 00:38:32.496
showed the exact opposite, that actually senolysis or removal of

659
00:38:32.586 --> 00:38:36.226
senescence can block tumor progression and relapse after therapy.

660
00:38:36.906 --> 00:38:39.046
So how can senescence have this paradoxical role?

661
00:38:39.146 --> 00:38:40.986
So there could be a number of reasons.

662
00:38:41.046 --> 00:38:42.106
As Jennifer alluded to,

663
00:38:43.246 --> 00:38:46.686
perhaps cells other than tumor cells are undergoing senescence and they're

664
00:38:46.946 --> 00:38:49.866
causing tumor promotion, and I'll get to that towards the end of my talk.

665
00:38:50.406 --> 00:38:54.246
You'll hear from Dr. Smith perhaps senescent cells aren't totally

666
00:38:54.705 --> 00:38:58.046
irreversibly arrested and could eventually proliferate again.

667
00:38:58.066 --> 00:39:02.046
But what my talk will focus on is the SAS, the ability of these damaged

668
00:39:02.086 --> 00:39:05.366
cells to convey their damage signals to the microenvironment.

669
00:39:06.486 --> 00:39:10.046
And the reason why the SAS might induce this paradoxical role of

670
00:39:10.086 --> 00:39:12.286
senescence, it has a lot of pleiotropy.

671
00:39:12.466 --> 00:39:16.356
There are a lot of different types of factors included in this secretome.

672
00:39:17.106 --> 00:39:20.806
These include proinflammatory cytokines, IL-1 alpha-beta, IL-6,

673
00:39:21.386 --> 00:39:24.606
chemokines like CCL2, but also growth factors

674
00:39:25.526 --> 00:39:28.806
and matrix metalloproteases that degrade the extracellular matrix,

675
00:39:29.746 --> 00:39:33.366
angiogenic factors such as VEGF, PDGFs, and

676
00:39:33.426 --> 00:39:35.846
also prostaglandins and other lipid species.

677
00:39:36.555 --> 00:39:39.706
And it's important to note that in addition to these secreted factors, senescent

678
00:39:39.726 --> 00:39:43.656
cells upregulate immunomodulatory receptors and ligands on

679
00:39:43.666 --> 00:39:46.646
their surface that can have immune consequences.

680
00:39:46.706 --> 00:39:50.386
For instance, activating NK cell ligands, activate NK cell surveillance,

681
00:39:51.106 --> 00:39:55.066
MHC class II expression of antigens that activate CD8 T cells, but

682
00:39:55.126 --> 00:39:58.366
also immunoevasive molecules such as PD-L1.

683
00:39:59.626 --> 00:40:03.186
And the SAS is regulated dynamically by the number of different transcription

684
00:40:03.286 --> 00:40:06.666
factors listed here. My talk, I'll focus on two of the more

685
00:40:06.706 --> 00:40:10.366
inflammatory ones, NF-kappa B and c-Gas, seeing the drive

686
00:40:10.406 --> 00:40:12.835
downstream IRFs and type I interferon signaling.

687
00:40:13.606 --> 00:40:17.346
We also know that there's also epigenetic regulation and enhancer remodeling to

688
00:40:17.426 --> 00:40:21.176
open up these loci as well as increase protein translation to drive the

689
00:40:21.226 --> 00:40:21.586
SAS.

690
00:40:22.786 --> 00:40:25.286
And so really, Judy Campisi, I believe, is the one who coined SAS as this

691
00:40:25.466 --> 00:40:29.306
double-edged sword in cancer. On the one hand, as Jennifer

692
00:40:29.346 --> 00:40:33.106
alluded to, the SAS can lead to fibrosis resolution, it can lead to wound

693
00:40:33.146 --> 00:40:33.566
closure,

694
00:40:34.386 --> 00:40:37.486
and it can also lead to attracting immune cells that come in and clear out that

695
00:40:37.526 --> 00:40:41.176
damage. But as the SAS lingers, for instance, during aging or other

696
00:40:41.226 --> 00:40:45.076
chronic diseases, that inflammation can be inherently immunosuppressive.

697
00:40:45.555 --> 00:40:49.506
It can also drive angiogenesis as well as invasion and proliferation of adjacent

698
00:40:49.586 --> 00:40:50.146
tumor cells.

699
00:40:51.186 --> 00:40:54.966
And so we really think this gets into this idea of acute versus chronic SAS.

700
00:40:55.046 --> 00:40:58.686
If you can acutely activate an immune response with a SAS that come in and clear

701
00:40:58.726 --> 00:41:01.326
out that damage, this can be tumor suppressive.

702
00:41:01.366 --> 00:41:05.025
But if this lingers, eventually the SAS can give rise to progression.

703
00:41:05.186 --> 00:41:08.676
So what I'll give you now is a few vignettes from my work and other works

704
00:41:09.286 --> 00:41:12.606
alluding to these tumor-suppressive and promoting aspects of the SAS, and then dig

705
00:41:12.666 --> 00:41:16.646
into how my lab has sort of looked into how the SAS is regulated and how

706
00:41:16.686 --> 00:41:20.046
we can push this response more to being tumor suppressive.

707
00:41:21.726 --> 00:41:25.486
So a number of works, particularly in hepatocellular carcinoma, have really shown

708
00:41:25.626 --> 00:41:29.416
us that senescent cells can be immunogenic, capable of both innate and

709
00:41:29.446 --> 00:41:33.326
adaptive immune surveillance. This is a work from Wen Xu, Lars

710
00:41:33.346 --> 00:41:35.266
Zeuner when they were in Scott Lowe's group.

711
00:41:35.306 --> 00:41:39.086
This is a model of HCC where P53 can be turned on or off with an

712
00:41:39.186 --> 00:41:43.046
shRNA. Reactivating P53 in the context of RAS

713
00:41:43.106 --> 00:41:46.086
mutations can induce senescence, as shown here by beta-gal.

