1103
01:03:35.814 --> 01:03:39.124
In the clinic, we often don't know whether we look at a wound or

1104
01:03:39.314 --> 01:03:43.183
cancer. So as obviously as we learned from the previous presentations, an

1105
01:03:43.934 --> 01:03:46.954
intimate relationship between derailed wound healing and

1106
01:03:47.034 --> 01:03:50.463
cancer. So senescent cells, as we all know, are an

1107
01:03:50.514 --> 01:03:54.034
intrinsic component of the multicellularity of

1108
01:03:54.114 --> 01:03:57.834
cancer as an organ. But I like to make the point, although it was

1109
01:03:57.894 --> 01:04:00.254
pointed out by my previous colleagues,

1110
01:04:01.054 --> 01:04:04.694
that in an acute fashion, senescent cells in wound

1111
01:04:04.734 --> 01:04:08.194
healing are an essential component for proper wound healing.

1112
01:04:08.754 --> 01:04:12.714
So the components listed here following the tissue injury,

1113
01:04:13.374 --> 01:04:17.314
primary senescence, then SAS-mediated secondary senescence

1114
01:04:17.374 --> 01:04:20.974
to take care of all damaged cells, not to

1115
01:04:21.034 --> 01:04:24.634
propagate any more and to contribute to the parenchymal

1116
01:04:24.674 --> 01:04:27.214
cellularity, is followed by

1117
01:04:27.314 --> 01:04:31.054
SASP-called immune cell invasion to

1118
01:04:31.194 --> 01:04:35.174
clear up the injured site. But there's also

1119
01:04:35.254 --> 01:04:38.154
translational reprogramming into

1120
01:04:38.214 --> 01:04:41.984
senescence-associated stemness, which sounds paradoxical,

1121
01:04:42.374 --> 01:04:45.934
but in proper wound healing, it's the senescent cells which

1122
01:04:46.054 --> 01:04:49.854
therefore may contribute to replenish cellularity

1123
01:04:50.274 --> 01:04:52.714
once stresses have been resolved.

1124
01:04:52.754 --> 01:04:55.434
And with this in mind, we may now look at

1125
01:04:55.494 --> 01:04:59.154
senescence-promoted cancer features with some different

1126
01:04:59.214 --> 01:05:02.974
perspective. In particular, looking at senescent cells not only

1127
01:05:03.054 --> 01:05:05.754
as the source of SAS, but also being

1128
01:05:06.294 --> 01:05:09.954
reprogrammed latent stem cells. And if this

1129
01:05:09.994 --> 01:05:13.654
happens hijacked by a tumor, they may become de

1130
01:05:13.694 --> 01:05:17.634
novo cancer stem cells. So with this, that's already obvious,

1131
01:05:17.714 --> 01:05:21.284
I think, to this audience, there is, in an acute fashion, in

1132
01:05:21.354 --> 01:05:25.054
response to activated oncogenes or in response

1133
01:05:25.114 --> 01:05:28.764
to antineoplastic therapy, a beneficial

1134
01:05:28.874 --> 01:05:31.584
tumor-suppressive form of senescence.

1135
01:05:31.714 --> 01:05:35.614
But if those therapy-exposed senescent

1136
01:05:35.654 --> 01:05:39.414
cells or oncogene-activated cells persist, then they may

1137
01:05:39.434 --> 01:05:42.374
drive derailed wound healing inflammation.

1138
01:05:42.434 --> 01:05:45.074
They are reprogrammed as stem cells.

1139
01:05:45.084 --> 01:05:48.974
And if they get permission to occasionally re-enter the

1140
01:05:49.014 --> 01:05:52.494
cell cycle, they may exert their stem-like function.

1141
01:05:53.334 --> 01:05:55.934
There's immunogenic plasticity, immune evasion.

1142
01:05:55.984 --> 01:05:58.334
We heard about this, and therefore, there are

1143
01:05:58.894 --> 01:06:02.074
possible therapeutic interventions.

1144
01:06:02.154 --> 01:06:05.594
We heard about senomorphics to limit, in particular, inflammation, and

1145
01:06:05.634 --> 01:06:09.554
senolytics to actually catch the senescent

1146
01:06:09.594 --> 01:06:12.334
cells at their root and eliminate them.

1147
01:06:12.394 --> 01:06:15.954
I'd like to make a point which, in my view, is obvious but is

1148
01:06:15.974 --> 01:06:19.834
not really deeply discussed. Senescence is not a binary

1149
01:06:19.954 --> 01:06:23.034
state. It's not in or out of senescence.

1150
01:06:23.074 --> 01:06:26.514
There is a pro-senescent trigger driving a cell into

1151
01:06:26.554 --> 01:06:30.434
senescence. And actually, it may matter over time how

1152
01:06:30.534 --> 01:06:34.494
long, how strong, and in what kind of trigger this trigger is

1153
01:06:34.534 --> 01:06:38.114
applying to cause maybe initial senescence, light

1154
01:06:38.214 --> 01:06:42.014
senescence, actual senescence, and perhaps something like

1155
01:06:42.134 --> 01:06:45.854
super senescence. I'm not showing data on this, but I like to make this

1156
01:06:45.954 --> 01:06:49.914
point that the depth of senescence, particularly at the level

1157
01:06:50.014 --> 01:06:53.974
of epigenomic reprogramming, chromatin remodeling, in particular, the

1158
01:06:54.054 --> 01:06:57.274
senescence-associated heterochromatin foci

1159
01:06:57.854 --> 01:07:01.834
may decide about the quality of senescence and

1160
01:07:01.974 --> 01:07:05.934
its depth, and in other words, what was already quoted before,

1161
01:07:05.944 --> 01:07:09.414
reversibility of senescence. I would not claim

1162
01:07:09.554 --> 01:07:13.104
senescence is reversible. I believe it's neither reversible

1163
01:07:13.214 --> 01:07:17.054
nor irreversible, but there is a state beyond senescence.

1164
01:07:17.134 --> 01:07:21.114
I like to share that with you. We have data why we believe this is not

1165
01:07:21.154 --> 01:07:24.374
philosophical, so that if senescence is

1166
01:07:24.474 --> 01:07:27.434
reversible, it was not senescence.

1167
01:07:27.934 --> 01:07:31.444
If you have a cell deeply in senescence, and here's the

1168
01:07:31.474 --> 01:07:34.954
machinery inaugurated by Monsieur Shin Narita in Scott Lowe, the

1169
01:07:34.974 --> 01:07:38.586
SAFmachinery. E2F target genes are

1170
01:07:38.626 --> 01:07:42.426
deeply silenced by an histone H3

1171
01:07:42.486 --> 01:07:44.706
lysine 9 trimethylated mechanism.

1172
01:07:44.926 --> 01:07:48.516
We concluded if we would provide in senescence a

1173
01:07:48.726 --> 01:07:52.686
demethylase activity, we may be able to

1174
01:07:52.726 --> 01:07:55.866
drive cells out of senescence. That's what you see on the right side.

1175
01:07:55.906 --> 01:07:59.266
If we induce Jumonji D2C, these firmly

1176
01:07:59.286 --> 01:08:03.226
RAS-induced senescent cells can level off, become

1177
01:08:03.306 --> 01:08:06.306
pS2 beta negative, and can reproliferate.

1178
01:08:06.446 --> 01:08:08.035
And the mechanism behind is

1179
01:08:09.066 --> 01:08:12.426
turnover of nucleosomes. This has to be

1180
01:08:12.486 --> 01:08:16.387
permanently reestablished. So we allowed an H3

1181
01:08:16.467 --> 01:08:20.166
arginine 9 mutant to compete with H3 lysine

1182
01:08:20.406 --> 01:08:24.346
9, and you see it takes a while, but after a while there

1183
01:08:24.406 --> 01:08:28.326
is an overtake of the R9 mutant, which can

1184
01:08:28.467 --> 01:08:32.366
obviously not lysine 9 trimethylate, and that's sufficient to

1185
01:08:32.706 --> 01:08:36.547
allow, again, senescent cells to get out of senescence.

1186
01:08:36.626 --> 01:08:40.346
And you see these senescent cells have now a reduced load of

1187
01:08:40.526 --> 01:08:44.387
H3 lysine 9 tri-methylation. We

1188
01:08:44.406 --> 01:08:48.007
heard a lot about heterogeneity of senescence, and I think that's super important

1189
01:08:48.047 --> 01:08:51.686
because the field is moving into single-cell omics

1190
01:08:51.766 --> 01:08:55.306
technologies and tries to describe the various

1191
01:08:55.346 --> 01:08:59.326
facets and types of senescence. I like to discuss with you whether

1192
01:08:59.366 --> 01:09:02.906
there might be rather one full-featured uniform

1193
01:09:03.087 --> 01:09:06.626
program that provides

1194
01:09:06.726 --> 01:09:09.596
certain aspects in different contexts.

1195
01:09:09.887 --> 01:09:13.467
So it's more or less the same senescence program, which is

1196
01:09:13.507 --> 01:09:17.406
associated with key functionalities in given cellular

1197
01:09:17.526 --> 01:09:20.986
context. Other features are present but less relevant.

1198
01:09:21.346 --> 01:09:25.186
Or whether there are indeed multiple or many distinct types

1199
01:09:25.246 --> 01:09:29.146
of senescence characterized by different lead functions where other

1200
01:09:29.206 --> 01:09:33.186
features are less present. I'm not concluding either

1201
01:09:33.246 --> 01:09:37.047
of the two is right. I guess it's a spectrum in between, but

1202
01:09:37.547 --> 01:09:40.587
it's important for therapeutic interventions.

1203
01:09:41.066 --> 01:09:44.906
So there is a core senescence machinery and a specialized

1204
01:09:44.986 --> 01:09:48.646
machinery, which would mean if you look at a rather uniform senescence

1205
01:09:48.726 --> 01:09:50.846
program, it's driven by the core machinery.

1206
01:09:51.366 --> 01:09:54.826
If it's more a specialized program, it's driven by these

1207
01:09:54.906 --> 01:09:58.506
additional lead functions. Core senescence markers we

1208
01:09:58.566 --> 01:10:02.546
know, it's complicated enough to detect them or to determine

1209
01:10:02.566 --> 01:10:06.226
whether a cell fulfills a sufficient amount of these

1210
01:10:06.266 --> 01:10:10.026
markers or is positive for certain signatures, as we heard

1211
01:10:10.086 --> 01:10:13.976
today. So this is complicated. But if we look at the more

1212
01:10:14.106 --> 01:10:16.866
specialized senescence markers, we would have

1213
01:10:17.246 --> 01:10:20.966
type-specific senescence vulnerabilities as compared

1214
01:10:21.026 --> 01:10:24.486
to targeting the core machinery in terms of a shared

1215
01:10:24.526 --> 01:10:28.206
senescence vulnerability. So the more uniform

1216
01:10:28.226 --> 01:10:31.966
program is good and bad senescence throughout the body, while the

1217
01:10:32.126 --> 01:10:36.066
more diverse or multiple types of senescence may

1218
01:10:36.106 --> 01:10:39.566
give you specific senescence functions and you may argue, I

1219
01:10:39.646 --> 01:10:43.626
understand that from a clinical perspective, you want to target the bad

1220
01:10:43.746 --> 01:10:46.206
ones and want to leave the good ones intact.

1221
01:10:46.526 --> 01:10:49.766
Whether that's achievable, that's a different question.

1222
01:10:49.946 --> 01:10:53.486
I'm not making an argument for either point, but

1223
01:10:53.626 --> 01:10:57.246
I like to go for the second half of the talk through an

1224
01:10:57.266 --> 01:11:01.146
intense analytic approach where I share with you the addressing

1225
01:11:01.246 --> 01:11:05.126
of a rather uniform aspect of cellular senescence and what

1226
01:11:05.166 --> 01:11:06.926
the consequences of this might be.

1227
01:11:06.966 --> 01:11:07.915
Before we get to this,

1228
01:11:08.886 --> 01:11:11.486
looking at senolytics, what will happen?

1229
01:11:11.546 --> 01:11:15.446
In acute senescence, or senescence in

1230
01:11:15.486 --> 01:11:18.946
an acute fashion, I think we agree on this, is rather a beneficial

1231
01:11:19.066 --> 01:11:22.946
program, and there is stemness associated with

1232
01:11:23.026 --> 01:11:26.526
senescence in wound healing. There is immunosurveillance of

1233
01:11:26.546 --> 01:11:30.406
senescent cells. But if senescence gets chronic, it's typically

1234
01:11:30.446 --> 01:11:33.446
detrimental. I already referred to cancer

1235
01:11:33.926 --> 01:11:37.646
cell-associated stemness, loss of functional parenchyma,

1236
01:11:37.766 --> 01:11:39.946
and others before have

1237
01:11:41.306 --> 01:11:45.286
talked about organ fibrosis. So if we eliminate

1238
01:11:45.326 --> 01:11:47.706
the beneficial acute senescence, we may

1239
01:11:48.566 --> 01:11:51.526
have problems. We may impair stem cell compartments.

1240
01:11:51.586 --> 01:11:54.906
We compromise regeneration or may attenuate immunity.

1241
01:11:55.105 --> 01:11:59.046
That needs to be seen. In the chronic detrimental senescence,

1242
01:11:59.106 --> 01:12:02.486
that's obviously the space in which we like to eliminate

1243
01:12:02.546 --> 01:12:06.066
senescent cells in order to see anti-aging

1244
01:12:06.126 --> 01:12:09.206
effects, fibrolytic effects, and anti-cancer effects.

1245
01:12:09.486 --> 01:12:13.286
So if I could choose, I would try to optimize

1246
01:12:13.346 --> 01:12:16.126
dose scheduling in order to leave

1247
01:12:16.546 --> 01:12:20.366
senescence beneficial in the first place and

1248
01:12:20.426 --> 01:12:24.206
apply senolysis in a scenario where I can eliminate

1249
01:12:24.216 --> 01:12:27.406
those which dictate unwanted disease

1250
01:12:27.466 --> 01:12:31.106
pathologies. So that's what we aim for, to control

1251
01:12:31.246 --> 01:12:31.766
cancer,

1252
01:12:32.566 --> 01:12:36.186
actually even prevent cancer, and attenuate aging by

1253
01:12:36.406 --> 01:12:39.806
pan-senolytic approach. And I'd like to share with you how we

1254
01:12:39.886 --> 01:12:43.846
harness the redox imbalance in senescent cells for

1255
01:12:43.866 --> 01:12:47.006
senolysis and what the clinical effects in

1256
01:12:47.026 --> 01:12:50.486
preclinical models might be. For this, we teamed up with a

1257
01:12:50.546 --> 01:12:54.436
medicinal chemist from the Free University in Berlin, Jörg Rademann,

1258
01:12:54.546 --> 01:12:58.326
and colleagues, and set up a redox-based drug screen

1259
01:12:58.366 --> 01:13:01.966
because we came across metabolic

1260
01:13:02.306 --> 01:13:05.486
imbalances in senescent cells driven by

1261
01:13:05.626 --> 01:13:09.606
NADH as a background, which could allow us to

1262
01:13:09.666 --> 01:13:13.546
screen for an oxidative activation of candidate

1263
01:13:13.706 --> 01:13:17.606
drugs in order to produce further oxidative stress to

1264
01:13:17.646 --> 01:13:20.346
selectively eliminate senescent cells.

1265
01:13:20.646 --> 01:13:24.326
So get a dual selectivity of an agent, which is now called

1266
01:13:24.406 --> 01:13:27.286
Senlytic, for the elimination of senescent cells.

1267
01:13:27.756 --> 01:13:31.706
So this agent we retrieved from the drug screen, Senlytic, is

1268
01:13:31.746 --> 01:13:35.366
indeed activated by NADH. You see the higher the

1269
01:13:35.506 --> 01:13:38.954
NADH we provide, the higher thePeroxide

1270
01:13:39.194 --> 01:13:42.624
H2O2 output is, and this is countered by

1271
01:13:42.734 --> 01:13:46.254
GSH. So in conclusion, high NADH, low

1272
01:13:46.294 --> 01:13:49.354
GSH levels would activate this agent.

1273
01:13:49.904 --> 01:13:53.734
And since it's producing peroxide, if we overexpress catalase,

1274
01:13:53.874 --> 01:13:57.374
we reduce peroxide production, and we limit

1275
01:13:57.414 --> 01:14:01.254
the cytotoxic efficacy of this agent.

1276
01:14:01.774 --> 01:14:05.594
We made a derivative which is no longer activated by

1277
01:14:05.714 --> 01:14:09.634
NADH. It's the de-Senlyt, the blue line, and you see this

1278
01:14:09.694 --> 01:14:13.134
has no senolytic potential as compared to the original

1279
01:14:13.234 --> 01:14:14.674
compound, the red line.

1280
01:14:15.754 --> 01:14:19.524
Here you look at a number of senescent scenarios, therapy-induced,

1281
01:14:19.634 --> 01:14:22.374
oncogene-induced, oncogene inhibition-induced senescence.

1282
01:14:22.774 --> 01:14:26.314
And the common feature of all these senescent types is

1283
01:14:26.374 --> 01:14:29.734
this altered NADH/GSH

1284
01:14:29.874 --> 01:14:32.574
ratio across the cell types.

1285
01:14:34.794 --> 01:14:38.694
Notice that senescent cells have an elevated pool

1286
01:14:38.774 --> 01:14:42.594
of labile iron, and this LIP can be

1287
01:14:42.613 --> 01:14:46.074
measured by Ferro-Orange. And you see that across

1288
01:14:46.154 --> 01:14:48.974
different senescence inductions, we see this

1289
01:14:49.954 --> 01:14:53.514
elevated pool. But senescent cells are protected from

1290
01:14:53.534 --> 01:14:56.274
ferroptosis. We are coming to this in a second.

1291
01:14:56.334 --> 01:14:59.994
If we provide a chelator here, Desferrioxamine, we can

1292
01:15:00.074 --> 01:15:04.034
reduce these lipid iron pools. So if we

1293
01:15:04.114 --> 01:15:05.534
use Senlyt, we can,

1294
01:15:06.334 --> 01:15:09.734
in a dose-dependent manner, increase reactive oxygen

1295
01:15:09.794 --> 01:15:13.364
species. You see in the upper left the lysosomal ROS or

1296
01:15:13.774 --> 01:15:17.394
right, the mitochondrial ROS. It's the red lines to focus on for

1297
01:15:17.514 --> 01:15:21.274
now. And lipid peroxidation increases or

1298
01:15:21.394 --> 01:15:24.614
is increased, as I said, in senescent cells, and that can be

1299
01:15:24.714 --> 01:15:28.514
utilized on the lower right by Senlyt to kill

1300
01:15:28.614 --> 01:15:30.934
these cells out of this

1301
01:15:32.254 --> 01:15:36.214
latent ferroptotic state. If we use another

1302
01:15:37.274 --> 01:15:40.994
iron chelator here, B-pyridone, BIPI, the blue

1303
01:15:41.054 --> 01:15:44.534
lines you see we reduce ROS production in

1304
01:15:44.594 --> 01:15:47.774
response to Senlyt. We get less lipid

1305
01:15:47.814 --> 01:15:50.554
peroxidation, and we don't see a senolytic effect.

1306
01:15:50.934 --> 01:15:54.494
So this concludes that Senlyt helps to utilize

1307
01:15:54.614 --> 01:15:58.394
iron in the so-called Fenton reaction to produce

1308
01:15:58.454 --> 01:16:02.434
OH radicals and to kill. But I like to mention

1309
01:16:02.514 --> 01:16:06.194
that another arm of killing by Senlyt is

1310
01:16:06.234 --> 01:16:09.734
via classic apoptosis, as blockable here

1311
01:16:09.794 --> 01:16:13.474
by cVAD-fmk. But in conclusion, we

1312
01:16:13.954 --> 01:16:17.914
use two modes of cell death, ferroptosis and apoptosis,

1313
01:16:18.254 --> 01:16:22.214
and even strongly apoptotically compromised tumor cells can

1314
01:16:22.374 --> 01:16:25.014
still be killed via the ferroptotic pathway.

1315
01:16:25.974 --> 01:16:28.494
Senlyt has high senescent selectivity.

1316
01:16:28.554 --> 01:16:32.534
You look at four scenarios, non-malignant settings or tumor settings

1317
01:16:32.574 --> 01:16:34.754
in the mouse or in the human species.

1318
01:16:34.774 --> 01:16:37.854
And you can see from all these graphs that there is a huge

1319
01:16:38.734 --> 01:16:42.703
senolytic index and great advantage to selectively

1320
01:16:42.734 --> 01:16:45.954
kill senescent cells as compared to proliferating cells.

1321
01:16:45.994 --> 01:16:49.874
That's reiterated here. It's difficult to read curve, sorry

1322
01:16:49.934 --> 01:16:53.294
about this, but what it tells us is that

1323
01:16:53.394 --> 01:16:57.374
Senlyt is at least as good or better, obviously,

1324
01:16:57.494 --> 01:17:01.354
than other established senolytics in killing at low

1325
01:17:01.474 --> 01:17:04.894
concentration senescent cells, but with limited

1326
01:17:04.994 --> 01:17:08.434
toxicity to their proliferating counterparts.

1327
01:17:08.774 --> 01:17:11.874
And there's a genetic senescence dependency if we test

1328
01:17:12.034 --> 01:17:15.714
p53-proficient versus p53-deficient cells.

1329
01:17:16.134 --> 01:17:19.984
It's the proficient and senescence-capable, but not the senescence-incapable

1330
01:17:20.154 --> 01:17:24.014
cells we can kill by this agent. Just to go through

1331
01:17:24.024 --> 01:17:27.914
a few more vignettes, this is replicative senescence in a

1332
01:17:27.994 --> 01:17:31.814
setting where we have cells arresting after a certain number

1333
01:17:31.894 --> 01:17:34.674
of divisions as compared to HTERT positive cells.

1334
01:17:34.714 --> 01:17:37.414
It's only the RS cells which can be killed.

1335
01:17:37.854 --> 01:17:39.654
We look at virus-induced senescence.

1336
01:17:39.734 --> 01:17:43.094
Some cells can undergo virus-induced senescence. You see that on the left.

1337
01:17:43.434 --> 01:17:47.034
Others don't, and only those which undergo this are

1338
01:17:47.074 --> 01:17:50.734
susceptible to Senlyt. That might be the most important slide of the

1339
01:17:50.754 --> 01:17:54.574
presentation for Senlyt, because you look at virtually all kinds of

1340
01:17:54.634 --> 01:17:58.574
cellular senescence we tested, and whenever we achieve to

1341
01:17:59.034 --> 01:18:02.134
drive cells into senescence, you see a blue

1342
01:18:02.994 --> 01:18:06.554
square to depict senescence. And it's only in those

1343
01:18:06.634 --> 01:18:10.514
settings where dose-dependent application of Senlyt will

1344
01:18:10.634 --> 01:18:13.814
result in profound cell death.

1345
01:18:14.614 --> 01:18:18.454
We can eliminate aged cells. Here, this is an example of

1346
01:18:18.514 --> 01:18:22.124
lung fibrosis in old mice. Again, to remind you, there is

1347
01:18:22.694 --> 01:18:26.374
